        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "to be ruler over Israel and over Judah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " It is possible, as Bahr thinks, that Israel and Judah were severally mentioned because David had once been king over Judah only, and because Israel had gone over to the side of Absalom. It is more probable, however, that \"Israel and Judah\" was even then the current designation of the two component parts of the realm (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 2:9, 10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 19:11, 41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.). Besides, we can hardly suppose that the historian has in every case, though he probably has in this, preserved the exact words of the speaker; and it need cause us no surprise had he put into David's mouth the phraseology of a later age. In the nature of things he can only give us the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "substance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of conversations such as these. 1 Kings 1:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
